My wife and I were regulars of Bar Charley back when it opened and, since moving a few miles east in the city, have an interesting perspective of how it is now after returning from some time off. The original Bar Charley was a five-star location and their trout amandine was to die for (and a price tag of only about $11 IIRC). The concept of the bar was to get good cocktails for less than $10 USD, since everywhere in DC has crazy cocktail/wine/beer prices these days. The other food was largely burgers and whatnot and it was just extremely well-executed.  Their menu changed quickly and changed often thereafter, but it always maintained high quality food and the crow favorites always made the cut from menu to menu. This is why the suffering bastard, sazerac, etc., are still the primary drinks and the Catalan fries (think poutine), the tuna tartare, and Charley burger seem to always be on the menu.  This most recent time we went, it was restaurant week and I got a mushroom soup and venison while my wife got the tuna tartare and the Charley cut steak. Both our meals were delicious, but even with the restaurant week deal, the prices were astronomical relative to what this humble little pseudo-dive bar started out as. Gone are the days of main courses for less than $15 or $20, and $30 is more likely to be the average price for your main dish if you want to venture away from the burger (unless you go on Sundays for 1/2 price steak night). The drinks have also now nearly all reached the $10 mark, so best to come during happy hour when you can to save on your suffering bastard (still one of the cheapest and best they have). The main dishes are also now primarily steaks, which is fine, but you should know what you are walking into.  In sum, I still like Bar Charley a lot, but I miss the character and value of the original concept. The new Bar Charley is still very high quality, but more akin to a typical DC restaurant with commensurate pricing.
